label: ACDCTerminal
comment: An electrical connection point (AC or DC) to a piece of conducting equipment. Terminals are connected at physical connection points called connectivity nodes.

label: Accumulator
comment: Accumulator represents an accumulated (counted) Measurement, e.g. an energy value.

label: AccumulatorLimit
comment: Limit values for Accumulator measurements.

label: AccumulatorLimitSet
comment: An AccumulatorLimitSet specifies a set of Limits that are associated with an Accumulator measurement.

label: AccumulatorReset
comment: This command resets the counter value to zero.

label: AccumulatorValue
comment: AccumulatorValue represents an accumulated (counted) MeasurementValue.

label: Analog
comment: Analog represents an analog Measurement.

label: AnalogControl
comment: An analog control used for supervisory control.

label: AnalogLimit
comment: Limit values for Analog measurements.

label: AnalogLimitSet
comment: An AnalogLimitSet specifies a set of Limits that are associated with an Analog measurement.

label: AnalogValue
comment: AnalogValue represents an analog MeasurementValue.

label: Command
comment: A Command is a discrete control used for supervisory control.

label: Control
comment: Control is used for supervisory/device control. It represents control outputs that are used to change the state in a process, e.g. close or open breaker, a set point value or a raise lower command.

label: Discrete
comment: Discrete represents a discrete Measurement, i.e. a Measurement representing discrete values, e.g. a Breaker position.

label: DiscreteValue
comment: DiscreteValue represents a discrete MeasurementValue.

label: IOPoint
comment: The class describe a measurement or control value. The purpose is to enable having attributes and associations common for measurement and control.

label: Limit
comment: Specifies one limit value for a Measurement. A Measurement typically has several limits that are kept together by the LimitSet class. The actual meaning and use of a Limit instance (i.e., if it is an alarm or warning limit or if it is a high or low limit) is not captured in the Limit class. However the name of a Limit instance may indicate both meaning and use.

label: LimitSet
comment: Specifies a set of Limits that are associated with a Measurement. A Measurement may have several LimitSets corresponding to seasonal or other changing conditions. The condition is captured in the name and description attributes. The same LimitSet may be used for several Measurements. In particular percentage limits are used this way.

label: Measurement
comment:
A Measurement represents any measured, calculated or non-measured non-calculated quantity. Any piece of equipment may contain Measurements, e.g. a substation may have temperature measurements and door open indications, a transformer may have oil temperature and tank pressure measurements, a bay may contain a number of power flow measurements and a Breaker may contain a switch status measurement. 
The PSR - Measurement association is intended to capture this use of Measurement and is included in the naming hierarchy based on EquipmentContainer. The naming hierarchy typically has Measurements as leaves, e.g. Substation-VoltageLevel-Bay-Switch-Measurement.
Some Measurements represent quantities related to a particular sensor location in the network, e.g. a voltage transformer (VT) or potential transformer (PT) at a busbar or a current transformer (CT) at the bar between a breaker and an isolator. The sensing position is not captured in the PSR - Measurement association. Instead it is captured by the Measurement - Terminal association that is used to define the sensing location in the network topology. The location is defined by the connection of the Terminal to ConductingEquipment. 
If both a Terminal and PSR are associated, and the PSR is of type ConductingEquipment, the associated Terminal should belong to that ConductingEquipment instance.
When the sensor location is needed both Measurement-PSR and Measurement-Terminal are used. The Measurement-Terminal association is never used alone.

label: MeasurementValue
comment: The current state for a measurement. A state value is an instance of a measurement from a specific source. Measurements can be associated with many state values, each representing a different source for the measurement.

label: MeasurementValueQuality
comment: Measurement quality flags. Bits 0-10 are defined for substation automation in IEC 61850-7-3. Bits 11-15 are reserved for future expansion by that document. Bits 16-31 are reserved for EMS applications.

label: MeasurementValueSource
comment: MeasurementValueSource describes the alternative sources updating a MeasurementValue. User conventions for how to use the MeasurementValueSource attributes are defined in IEC 61970-301.

label: PowerSystemResource
comment: A power system resource (PSR) can be an item of equipment such as a switch, an equipment container containing many individual items of equipment such as a substation, or an organisational entity such as sub-control area. Power system resources can have measurements associated.

label: RaiseLowerCommand
comment: An analog control that increases or decreases a set point value with pulses. Unless otherwise specified, one pulse moves the set point by one.

label: SetPoint
comment: An analog control that issues a set point value.

label: StringMeasurement
comment: StringMeasurement represents a measurement with values of type string.

label: StringMeasurementValue
comment: StringMeasurementValue represents a measurement value of type string.

label: Terminal
comment: An AC electrical connection point to a piece of conducting equipment. Terminals are connected at physical connection points called connectivity nodes.

label: ValueAliasSet
comment: Describes the translation of a set of values into a name and is intendend to facilitate custom translations. Each ValueAliasSet has a name, description etc. A specific Measurement may represent a discrete state like Open, Closed, Intermediate etc. This requires a translation from the MeasurementValue.value number to a string, e.g. 0->"Invalid", 1->"Open", 2->"Closed", 3->"Intermediate". Each ValueToAlias member in ValueAliasSet.Value describe a mapping for one particular value to a name.

label: ValueToAlias
comment: Describes the translation of one particular value into a name, e.g. 1 as "Open".
